{
"drug_name": "Vedolizumab",
"advantages": "Vedolizumab is a gut-selective immunosuppressant, meaning it specifically targets the gut and reduces systemic side effects. This makes it a safer option for a patient with a history of cancer, like prostate cancer in this case. It has been shown to be effective in treating moderate to severe ulcerative colitis.",
"disadvantages": "Vedolizumab requires intravenous administration, which can be inconvenient. It may also take several weeks to months to see the full effect of the drug. As with any immunosuppressant, there is a risk of infections."
},
{
"drug_name": "Ustekinumab",
"advantages": "Ustekinumab is another option for moderate to severe ulcerative colitis. It targets a specific pathway in the immune system (interleukin-12 and -23), reducing inflammation. It can be administered subcutaneously after the initial intravenous dose, which can be more convenient for the patient.",
"disadvantages": "Ustekinumab may take several weeks to show effect. It also carries a risk of infections due to its immunosuppressive nature. The safety of ustekinumab in patients with a history of malignancy is not fully established."
}
]

