{
"drug_name": "Infliximab",
"advantages": "Infliximab is a TNF-α inhibitor that has demonstrated efficacy in clinical trials for moderate to severe UC. It targets the pro-inflammatory cytokine tumour necrosis factor- α (TNF -α), which plays a key role in the inflammatory process of UC. Infliximab has been shown to provide a rapid response to treatment, which aligns with the patient's priority.",
"disadvantages": "Potential side effects of infliximab include increased risk of infection due to immune suppression. It is also administered via intravenous infusion, which may be less convenient for some patients. Additionally, some patients may develop antibodies to infliximab over time, which can reduce its effectiveness."
},
{
"drug_name": "Adalimumab",
"advantages": "Adalimumab is another TNF-α inhibitor that has been tested for moderate to severe UC. It is administered subcutaneously, which may be more convenient for some patients compared to infliximab's intravenous administration. Adalimumab has also been shown to be effective in inducing and maintaining remission in UC.",
"disadvantages": "Similar to infliximab, adalimumab can increase the risk of infections. Other potential side effects include injection site reactions, headaches, and nausea. Some patients may also develop antibodies to adalimumab, which can reduce its effectiveness over time."
}
]

